        "title": "The golden chain — God's unbreakable purpose",
        "range": "8:28-30",
        "excerpt": "For those whom He foreknew, He also predestined to become conformed to the image of His Son… and these whom He justified, He also glorified.",
        "body": "Paul anchors the whole pastoral structure in God's eternal purpose. *And we know* (*oidamen*, settled corporate knowledge) *that God causes all things to work together for good to those who love God, to those who are called according to His purpose*. The famous verse must be read with v. 29-30 attached or it floats free of its grounding. The 'good' of v. 28 is defined by v. 29: *to be conformed to the image of His Son*. Not health, wealth, or circumstantial comfort but Christlikeness. And the certainty rests not in the believer's love for God (mentioned, but secondary) but in God's call *according to His purpose* (*prothesis* — His settled intent from before time).\n\nVerses 29-30 form the chain. Five verbs, all in the aorist, describing five sovereign acts of God: *proegnō* (foreknew), *proorisen* (predestined), *ekalesen* (called), *edikaiosen* (justified), *edoxasen* (glorified). The chain is unbroken — every link is the same set of people, named at each stage. Those foreknown are predestined; those predestined are called; those called are justified; those justified are glorified. No one drops out at any stage. The future tense is absent from the chain; even glorification is spoken in the past tense, because from God's vantage it is as good as done.\n\nThe Reformed and classical Arminian traditions differ on *proegnō*. The Reformed reading (Calvin, Owen, Edwards, more recently Moo, Schreiner) takes *foreknew* as *fore-loved* or *fore-set His covenant love upon* — the Hebraic background of *yada* in passages like Amos 3:2 ('You only have I known of all the families of the earth'). On this reading, foreknowledge is electing love, not bare prescience. The classical Arminian reading takes *foreknew* as God's prescience of foreseen faith — God knew in advance who would believe and predestined them accordingly. Both traditions affirm the chain's unbreakability; they differ on its ground. The pastoral payoff for either is the same: those in the chain do not fall out of it.\n\nThe purpose of predestination is named: *to become conformed to the image of His Son, so that He would be the firstborn among many brethren*. The end of salvation is christological. The Son's preeminence is preserved (*prototokos* — firstborn, the firstborn of many), and the redeemed are conformed to His image — restored to what Adam was meant to be (Genesis 1:26-27) and what Christ uniquely is (Colossians 1:15). The image of God in humanity, marred at the fall, is reconstituted in those conformed to the image of the Son.\n\nThis chain is the foundation of the chapter's climax. The reason no separation is possible (vv. 31-39) is that God Himself is the one who began the chain, sustains it at every link, and has already counted the final link complete. The believer's perseverance rests not on the believer's grip on God but on God's grip on the believer.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Prothesis* (v. 28) — settled purpose, deliberate intent. *Proginosko* (v. 29) — *fore-know*, with the Hebraic depth of *yada* (covenant-knowing, not bare cognition). *Summorphos* (v. 29) — co-formed, sharing the same *morphe* as the Son. *Edoxasen* (v. 30) — aorist, treating future glorification as past from God's vantage. The five aorists together form a chain that history cannot break."
